04298nam a22005655i 9780822392668DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223926687 a10.1515/97808223926682doi  a(DE-B1597)553190  a(OCoLC)1202624428  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHV875.5b.K49 2010 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306.8742221 aKim, Eleana J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAdopted Territory :bTransnational Korean Adoptees and the Politics of Belonging /cEleana J. Kim. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (340 p.) :b15 photographs, 4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes on Transliteration, Terminology, and Pseudonyms -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Understanding Transnational Korean Adoption -- tPART I -- t1. ‘‘Waifs’’ and ‘‘Orphans’ -- t2. Adoptee Kinship -- t3. Adoptee Cultural Citizenship -- t4. Public Intimacies and Private Politics -- tPART II -- t5. Our Adoptee, Our Alien -- t6. Made in Korea -- t7. Beyond Good and Evil -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the end of the Korean War, an estimated 200,000 children from South Korea have been adopted into white families in North America, Europe, and Australia. While these transnational adoptions were initiated as an emergency measure to find homes for mixed-race children born in the aftermath of the war, the practice grew exponentially from the 1960s through the 1980s. At the height of South Korea’s “economic miracle,” adoption became an institutionalized way of dealing with poor and illegitimate children. Most of the adoptees were raised with little exposure to Koreans or other Korean adoptees, but as adults, through global flows of communication, media, and travel, they have come into increasing contact with each other, Korean culture, and the South Korean state. Since the 1990s, as Korean children have continued to leave to be adopted in the West, a growing number of adult adoptees have been returning to Korea to seek their cultural and biological origins. In this fascinating ethnography, Eleana J. Kim examines the history of Korean adoption, the emergence of a distinctive adoptee collective identity, and adoptee returns to Korea in relation to South Korean modernity and globalization. Kim draws on interviews with adult adoptees, social workers, NGO volunteers, adoptee activists, scholars, and journalists in the U.S., Europe, and South Korea, as well as on observations at international adoptee conferences, regional organization meetings, and government-sponsored motherland tours.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAdopteeszKorea (South). 0aAdopteeszUnited States. 0aIntercountry adoptionzKorea (South). 0aIntercountry adoptionzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822392668zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822392668423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822392668/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles